title: "Arts and Inclusion - Opportunities and Challenges" Symposium (with photos)
content_text:
p>
The following is issued on behalf of the International Festival of Inclusive 
Arts: What is the power of arts in influencing society's perceptions of people with 
disabilities? How do arts connect with education and disabilities? What are the 
opportunities and challenges and how do different fields collaborate to create 
blue seas? In the "Arts and Inclusion �V Opportunities and Challenges" Symposium 
held by the International Festival of Inclusive Arts, overseas and local experts 
have been invited to share their experience and discuss the issues in depth. The

have been invited to share their experience and discuss the issues in depth. The 
public is welcome to reserve complimentary tickets and join the discussion. To be held on December 4 from 9am to 5pm at the Hong Kong Science Museum, the 
Symposium gathers international and local experts in education, arts and 
culture, including Ms Soula Antoniou, President of VSA Arts, Ms Ida Lam, 
Chairperson of the Arts with the Disabled Association Hong Kong, Ms Wendy

Chairperson of the Arts with the Disabled Association Hong Kong, Ms Wendy 
Crawford, Founder and Producer of mobileWOMEN.org, USA, Ms Cathy Horsley, Access 
Arts Development Officer, Arts and Festivals, Australia, Dr Vanessa Li Lok-wa, 
Senior Curriculum Development Officer (Visual Arts), Education and Manpower 
Bureau, and Mr Tang Hoi-chiu, Chief Curator, Hong Kong Museum of Art, who offer 
different perspectives on opportunities and challenges in inclusive arts. This

different perspectives on opportunities and challenges in inclusive arts. This 
is a rare opportunity for people in the fields of arts, education and 
rehabilitation to grasp the global horizon without the need to leave Hong Kong. Interested parties are welcome to reserve complimentary tickets on a first come, 
first served basis. For enquiries, please contact Ms Yuen Ka Yan at 2855 9548.
 Organised by the Health, Welfare and Food Bureau and the Arts with the Disabled 
Association Hong Kong, the International Festival of Inclusive Arts will be held

Association Hong Kong, the International Festival of Inclusive Arts will be held from December 2 to 10. Through diverse programmes like performances, exhibitions, a symposium, workshops and a carnival, the festival aims to provide an opportunity for participation in arts by people with and without disabilities, promoting an inclusive society. For details please visit http://www.hkifia.net. Ends/Monday, November 20, 2006
